iThere is an argument made by those practicing large-scale data		gopher.black	70
icapture and aggregation of individuals that the data they collect		gopher.black	70
iis public information, and therefore it is legal and justified.		gopher.black	70
iEven if the information collected was indeed all public--and I do		gopher.black	70
inot agree to that line of argument at all--then the question is		gopher.black	70
istill not settled. The very act of repeated visual proximity		gopher.black	70
i(which is transferrable to digital media via cyber-stalking		gopher.black	70
idefinitions) which could cause a "reasonable person fear" falls		gopher.black	70
iclearly within the bounds of stalking. If it is a corporation		gopher.black	70
icommiting these acts, then it is no less culpable than if it were		gopher.black	70
ian individual. After all, corporations are people too, right? [0]		gopher.black	70
