iThe act of data aggregation of an individual carries with it the		gopher.black	70
iinherent threat of what is being done with that data. As more		gopher.black	70
irevelations are brought to light informing the public of the		gopher.black	70
ideeply unsettling targeting of individuals for political		gopher.black	70
imanipulation, commercial activation, or social harassment, the		gopher.black	70
ifear increases. What else could be done with that information?		gopher.black	70
iEven if nothing is actually put into motion, the act of		gopher.black	70
icollection, of monitoring, is in itself a form of digital stalking		gopher.black	70
ithat explicitly undermines the argument of "public information".		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iAnonymous collection of data into aggregate data sets that cannot		gopher.black	70
ibe retargeted or focused to communicate outbound with a specific		gopher.black	70
ipopulation or person is still problematic. If that data allows you		gopher.black	70
ito segment or infer the actions of a type of person or group,		gopher.black	70
iespecially one that routinely faces subjugation or discrimination,		gopher.black	70
ithen the act of collection contributes to a justifiable fear of		gopher.black	70
ipersecution. It is stalking.		gopher.black	70
